World Economic Forum speakers signal a coming dystopian nightmare
American Thinker ^ | 27 May, 2022 | Eric Utter
https://www.americanthinker.com/blog/2022/05/world_economic_forum_speakers_signal_a_coming_dystopian_nightmare.html

Brave New World? You decide.

J. Michael Evans, president of the Alibaba Group-- a Chinese multinational technology company‚Äîbragged at the recent World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland: ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre developing through technology an ability for consumers to measure their own carbon footprint. What does that mean? That's where are they traveling, how are they traveling, what are they eating, what are they consuming on the platform?‚Äù

Not to be outdone, Pfizer CEO Albert Bourla told those attending the WEF about a new technology his company has developed: ‚ÄúIt is a, basically biological chip that is in the tablet. And once we take the tablet and dissolves into the stomach, sends a signal that you took the tablet. So, imagine the applications of that ‚Äì the compliance. The insurance companies know that the medicines patients should take, they take them.‚Äù He added, ‚ÄúIt is fascinating what happens in this field.‚Äù

He should have said, ‚ÄúIt is frightening what happens in this field.‚Äù

And then there was World Economic Forum Founder and Chairman Klaus Schwab telling the audience of over 2,500 global government and business leaders: ‚ÄúThe future is built by us, by a powerful community such as you here in this room.‚Äù

If you say so yourselves.

This year‚Äôs WEF theme was ‚ÄúHistory at a Turning Point: Government Policies and Business Strategies.‚Äù

Just what the world needs, a global fascist oligarchy monitoring what we consume and where we go, with the aid of ingestible computer chips that notify authorities whether we have been naughty or nice.

What the world actually does need is for we the people, the non-elite, to declare our freedom and independence and reclaim control from the titans of Big Government and Big Business.

_source.content: Senate Candidate Herschel Walker Proposes Social Media MonitoringMay 26, 2022Another politician uses a mass shooting to push for increased surveillance.Georgia Senate Candidate Herschel Walker has suggested that a government agency be set up to monitor the social media accounts of young men and women in the wake of Tuesday‚Äôs mass shooting at a Texas elementary school where the shooter killed 19 students and two adults before being fatally shot by law enforcement officers.Walker made the comments while being asked about his stance on gun control during a Fox News interview on Thursday.Walker began the interview by blasting those ‚Äúthat want to continue to talk about our constitutional rights rather than talking about the person that did this shooting.‚Äù He continued by suggesting increased mental health funding, pushing back against those who want to take away constitutional rights, and suggesting that the solution is to ‚Äúlook into the person that did the shooting.‚ÄùHowever, he then followed these comments with a suggestion that extended far beyond the scope of the perpetrator ‚Äì social media surveillance.‚ÄúWhat about getting a department that can look at young men, that‚Äôs looking at women, that‚Äôs looking at their social media,‚Äù Walker said. ‚ÄúWhat about doing that? Looking into things like that? We can stop that that way. But yet they wanna just continue to talk about taking away your constitutional rights.‚ÄùThe Republican Senate candidate didn‚Äôt provide any additional details on the scope of this proposed social media monitoring agency, how it would work, or how it could potentially prevent mass shootings.Walker is one of several politicians to call for increased social media in the wake of a mass shooting.
